---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import NewsletterForm from '../components/NewsletterForm.astro';
import Contour from '../components/Contour.astro';
import { SITE } from '../config';
---
<Base
  title="About"
  description="Chris Nash is a restoration leader, agroecologist and regenerative-development practitioner based in Cape Town, South Africa. Head of Restoration at Greenpop."
  path="/about/"
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">About</p>
      <h1 style="max-width:18ch">Restoration leader, agroecologist, <em>Capetonian</em>.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        I'm Chris Nash. I work at the meeting point of ecological restoration and human
        development: helping organisations and communities bring degraded landscapes back
        to life, and paying attention to what that work does to the people doing it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head">
        <span class="label">The work</span>
        <h2>From one burnt hillside to four countries.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The short version: after the 2018 Garden Route fires I spent years restoring a
          hillside near Kraaibosch by hand. Eight hectares of invasives cleared, 4,500
          indigenous trees planted, a food forest of four hundred trees across fifty
          species. That work grew into the Pachamama Project, and the conviction at the
          centre of everything I do now: land and people regenerate together, or not at all.
        </p>
        <p>
          Today I'm Head of Restoration at <a href={SITE.greenpop}>Greenpop</a>, where I
          help run nature-based-solutions programmes across Southern Africa: forest
          landscape restoration, urban greening and agroforestry. Through those programmes
          and their partners, around 30,000 trees a year go into the ground, along with
          hundreds of community greening days and ten urban green zones across South
          Africa's major cities.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid3" style="margin-top:40px">
        <div>
          <Contour variant="nairobi" coord="Nairobi, Kenya" height={140} />
          <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);margin-top:10px">A flagship syntropic-agroforestry site and training centre, built to be replicated.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <Contour variant="mulanje" coord="Mulanje, Malawi" height={140} />
          <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);margin-top:10px">Bioregional strategy and restoration-economy value chains in a UNESCO cultural landscape.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <Contour variant="uilenkraal" coord="Overberg, South Africa" height={140} />
          <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);margin-top:10px">Forest restoration and resilience around Africa's southernmost forest.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head">
        <span class="label">The idea</span>
        <h2>Inner &amp; Outer <em>Landscapes</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Every restoration project I've been part of has taught the same lesson twice.
          The land recovers through soil, water, species and time. The people recover
          through meaning, connection, capability and each other. Neither holds without
          the other. <strong>Inner &amp; Outer Landscapes</strong> is my name for
          practising both restorations as one, and the
          <a href="/letters/">fortnightly letters</a> are where the method is being built
          in public.
        </p>
      </div>
      <blockquote class="pull">"Collaboration is the cornerstone of effective community development."</blockquote>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band deep">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head">
        <span class="label">Threads I work across</span>
      </div>
      <div class="grid3">
        <div class="card"><h3>Hands in soil</h3><p>Permaculture and syntropic agroforestry practice; years of restoration fieldwork from seedling to canopy.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3>Delivery at scale</h3><p>Multi-country programme leadership: strategy, partnerships, monitoring and the unglamorous work of making restoration stand up to time.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3>Cities and community</h3><p>Urban greening and community-led development across South Africa's major cities.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3>The inner dimension</h3><p>Theory U, the Inner Development Goals and nature connection, woven into how teams and communities do the work.</p></div>
        <div class="card"><h3>Bioregional thinking</h3><p>Baseline assessments and strategy that start from the whole place: ecology, culture, economy, governance.</p></div>
        <div class="card dusk"><h3>African-rooted, globally fluent</h3><p>Working from Cape Town, across Southern and East Africa, in conversation with the global regeneration movement.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-head">
        <span class="label">Elsewhere</span>
      </div>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          I'm most active on <a href={SITE.linkedin} rel="me">LinkedIn</a>, where the field
          stories land first. For speaking, collaboration or consulting conversations,
          email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a>. And the best way to
          follow the work over time is the letter.
        </p>
      </div>
      <NewsletterForm id="subscribe" compact={true} />
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
